### The Lean proof follows from the fact that the image of a filter under a function is monotone with respect to the order on filters. This is because if `F ≤ G`, then any set in `F` is also in `G`, and hence the image of any set in `F` under `f` is also in `G.map f`, provided we can show that it is in `G`. The following Lean proof will establish this fact.

```lean
lemma mono (f : α → β) {F G : Filter α} (h : F ≤ G) : F.map f ≤ G.map f := by
  intro S hS
  -- We use the fact that if S is in F.map f, then there exists a set T in F such that f '' T = S.
  -- Since F ≤ G, T is also in G, so f '' T is in G.map f.
  -- We need to formalize this by showing that S is in G.map f.
  have h₁ : S ∈ G.map f := by
    -- We use the property of filters to find a set T in F such that f '' T = S.
    -- Then, since F ≤ G, T is also in G, so f '' T is in G.map f.
    obtain ⟨T, hT, rfl⟩ := hS
    -- Now we have S = f '' T, and T is in F.
